018 Report\">{{cite web |title=Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2018 |url=http://ir.united.com/static-files/7764f912-7135-486b-aa5c-f729fa8b7cb3 |date=February 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n</center>\n\n===Headquarters and other facilities===\n[[File:Willis Tower.jpg|thumb|upright|United Airlines Holdings World Headquarters, [[Willis Tower]]]]\n\nUnited Airlines headquarters are located at the [[Willis Tower]], 233 South Wacker Drive, Chicago, Illinois. \n<ref name=\"headquarters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.united.com/ual/en/us/fly/contact/headquarters.html|title=Headquarters Location|accessdate=2019-10-20 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, United had moved its headquarters from [[Elk Grove Township]], a suburb of Chicago, to [[77 West Wacker Drive]] in the [[Chicago Loop]]<ref name=\"Crains\">{{cite magazine | author1=Thomas A. Corfman | author2=Greg Hinz | url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20060713/NEWS12/200021317 | title=United HQ heading for Chicago | magazine=[[Crain's Chicago Business]] | date=July 13, 2006 | accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> after receiving US$5.5 million in incentives from the City of Chicago.<ref name=\"Incentives\"/> \n \nThen in 2010, United accepted the City of Chicago's offer of US$35 million in incentives, including a US$10 million grant, for United to move its remaining 2,500 employees out of Elk Grove Township to the [[Willis Tower]] (formerly the Sears Tower) in the Chicago Loop.<ref name=\"Incentives\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/05/business/05united.html?_r=1&src=busln | title=Chicago Wins Prize as Home of Big Carrier | author=Monica Davey | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 4, 2010 | accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref> On May 31, 2012, United opened its operations center, which occupied twelve floors there.<ref>{{cite news | title=United shows off new downtown operations center | author=Emily Morris | newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=June 18, 2012 | url=http://www.suntimes.com/business/13269459-420/united-shows-off-new-downtown-operations-center.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623164026/http://www.suntimes.com/business/13269459-420/united-shows-off-new-downtown-operations-center.html | archivedate=June 23, 2012 | url-status=dead | accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\nIn 2019 United renewed its lease at Willis Tower, originally ending in 2028 and now set to expire in 2033, and plans to construct a roof deck and a {{convert|30,000|foot2|abbr=on}} dining hall on the fourth floor.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ori, Ryan|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/columnists/ori/ct-biz-united-airlines-stays-at-willis-tower-ryan-ori-20190312-story.html|title=Column: United Airlines extends HQ lease at Willis Tower until 2033|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThe former headquarters campus at Elk Grove Township was gradually annexed into the [[Mount Prospect, Illinois|Village of Mount Prospect]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20120516/business/705169767/ |title=Mount Prospect annexes part of United campus |publisher=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]] ([[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]) |date=2012-05-16 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20170119/news/170118740/ |title=Mount Prospect annexes United property, 44 more acres |publisher=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]] ([[Arlington Heights, Illinois]]) |date=2017-01-19 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref> and serves as an IT operations facility, with a new {{convert|172,000|foot2|abbr=on}} data center constructed in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |editor=Richard Mayer |url=http://www.journal-topics.com/news/article_1aceeb92-0482-11e3-b247-001a4bcf6878.html |title=What Future Holds For Near-Empty United Site |work=Journal & Topics |publisher=Journal & Topics Online Media Group |date=2013-08-14 |accessdate=2017-07-08 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817130743/http://www.journal-topics.com/news/article_1aceeb92-0482-11e3-b247-001a4bcf6878.html |archive-date=2013-08-17}}</ref>\n\nUnited maintains a large presence in downtown Houston, having leased {{convert|225,000|foot2|abbr=on}} of space (seven floors) for occupancy in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulvaney |first=Erin |url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/real-estate/article/United-to-lease-space-in-new-downtown-high-rise-6854965.php |title=United to lease space in new downtown high-rise |newspaper=Houston Chronicle |date=2016-02-25 |accessdate=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n\nUnited has training facilities for its flight crews in Denver and Houston, a major aircraft maintenance center in San Francisco, and call centers in Houston and Chicago.\n\n===Corporate identity===\n====Brand image====\n{{see also|History of United Airlines#Brand history|l1=United Airlines brand history}}\nThe pre-merger United logo, commonly nicknamed the \"tulip\", was developed in the early 1970s by the designer [[Saul Bass]] as part of a new brand image.<ref name=\"Mouawad2\" /> The logo represented the airline's monogram as well as a modernized version of the airline's shield logo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://new.pentagram.com/2011/03/fifteen-years-of-flying-united-1|title=Fifteen Years of Flying United|website=Pentagram.com|access-date=April 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503235828/http://new.pentagram.com/2011/03/fifteen-years-of-flying-united-1/|archive-date=May 3, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> which had been adopted in the 1930s, but fell out of use by the late 1960s. The ribbon-like rendering has also been said to symbolize the motion of flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Innovation/Tech-Culture/2013/0508/How-Saul-Bass-changed-design|title=How Saul Bass changed design|website=Csmonitor.com}}</ref>\n\n====Marketing themes====\n{{further|History of United Airlines#Slogans}}\nUnited's earliest slogan, \"The Main Line Airway\", emphasized its signature New York-Chicago-San Francisco route, and was replaced in 1965 with \"Fly the Friendly Skies\", which was in use until 1996 in its first iteration.<ref name=nyt20130920>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/20/business/media/old-slogan-returns-as-united-asserts-it-is-customer-focused.html|title=Old Slogan Returns as United Asserts It Is Customer-Focused | first=Jane L. | last=Levere|date=September 20, 2013|work=The New York Times}}</ref> The \"It's time to fly\" slogan was created in 2004. After the merger of United and Continental in October 2010, the slogan changed to \"Let's fly together\" until September 2013,<ref name=nyt20130920/> when United announced a return of the \"Fly the Friendly Skies\" slogan in an ad campaign to start the following day.<ref name=\"frequentbusinesstraveler.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.frequentbusinesstraveler.com/2013/09/united-plans-return-to-the-friendly-skies/|title=United Plans Return to the \"Friendly Skies\"|work=frequentbusinesstraveler.com|accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref> The resurrected slogan would be accompanied by the 1924 [[George Gershwin]] song \"[[Rhapsody in Blue]]\" as its theme song, and a voiceover provided by [[Matt Damon]].<ref name=nyt20130920/>\n\nUnited had licensed its theme song, \"Rhapsody in Blue\", from Gershwin's estate for {{US$|500000|1976}} in 1976.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=[[Eldred v. Ashcroft]] |vol=01 |reporter=U.S. |opinion=618 |pinpoint=p. 67 |court=Supreme Court |date=January 15, 2003 |url= http://www.copyright.gov/docs/eldrdedo.pdf|quote=Even the $500,000 that United Airlines has had to pay for the right to play George Gershwin's 1924 classic ''Rhapsody in Blue'' represents a cost of doing business, potentially reflected in the ticket prices of those who fly.}}</ref> \"Rhapsody\" would have entered the [[public domain]] in 2000, but the [[Copyright Term Extension Act]] of 1998 extended its copyright another 20 years until January 1, 2020 when it officially entered on the Public Domain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/12/30/792302139/1924-copyrighted-works-to-become-part-of-the-public-domain|title=1924 Copyrighted Works To Become Part Of The Public Domain|last=|first=|date=2019-12-30|publisher=[[NPR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.law.duke.edu/cspd/publicdomainday/2020/|title=Public Domain Day 2020|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Duke Law School's [[Center for the Study of the Public Domain]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-01}}</ref>\nUnited announced that it would continue to use \"Rhapsody in Blue\" as its theme song following the merger with Continental.<ref>{{cite news|title= 'Rhapsody' remains familiar refrain at United|first= Phil|last= Rosenthal|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|date= {{date|2012-1-8|mdy}}|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-01-08/business/ct-biz-0108-phil--20120108_1_gershwin-music-rhapsody-ira-gershwin|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180729141439/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-01-08/business/ct-biz-0108-phil--20120108_1_gershwin-music-rhapsody-ira-gershwin|archivedate= July 29, 2018|url-status= dead|accessdate= {{date|2013-1-5|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental initiatives===\nBecause over 98 percent of United's [[Greenhouse gas|greenhouse gas emissions]] are from jet fuel, its environmental strategy has focused on operational fuel efficiency initiatives and investments in sustainably produced, [[Alternative fuel|low-carbon alternative fuels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/03/11/united-airlines-is-flying-on-biofuels-heres-why-thats-a-really-big-deal/?noredirect=on|title=United Airlines is flying on biofuels. Here's why that's a really big deal.|last=|first=|date=11 Mar 2016|website=The Washington Post|access-date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2011, United Continental Holdings, Inc. announced a conversion to paperless flight decks, and projected that by the end of the year, 11,000 [[iPad]]s will have been deployed to all United and Continental pilots. Each iPad, which weighs less than {{convert|1.5|lb}}, will replace approximately {{convert|38|lb}} of paper operating manuals, navigation charts, reference handbooks, flight checklists, logbooks, and weather information. The green benefits include reductions in paper use, printing, and fuel consumption.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://ir.unitedcontinentalholdings.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=83680&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1599253&highlight= | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130216233733/http://ir.unitedcontinentalholdings.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=83680&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1599253&highlight= | url-status=dead | archive-date=February 16, 2013 | title=United Airlines Launches Paperless Flight Deck With iPad | publisher=United Continental Holdings | date=August 23, 2011 | accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 2011, United flew the world's first commercial aviation flight on a microbially-derived biofuel. The aircraft was fueled with 40 percent Solajet, which is [[Solazyme]]'s algae-derived renewable jet fuel, and 60 percent petroleum-derived jet fuel. This flight was operated by the Eco-Skies Boeing 737-800 aircraft from Houston to Chicago-O'Hare.<ref>{{cite press release | title=Solazyme Announces First U.S. Commercial Passenger Flight on Advanced Biofuel | publisher=Solazyme | date=November 7, 2011 | url=http://www.solazyme.com/media/2011-11-07 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121018130949/http://solazyme.com/media/2011-11-07 | archivedate=October 18, 2012 | url-status=dead | accessdate=December 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2013, Aviation Partners Boeing (APB), a joint venture between [[Aviation Partners Inc.]] and Boeing, announced that United had agreed to replace the [[Wingtip device|Blended Winglets]] on its Boeing Next Generation 737 aircraft with APB's Split Scimitar Winglet (SSW), significantly reducing drag. Once the SSWs are installed, it is estimated that APB's winglet technology will save United more than $250 million annually in fuel costs.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/aviation-partners-boeing-launches-split-scimitar-winglet-program-186934521.html | title=Aviation Partners Boeing Launches Split Scimitar Winglet Program | publisher=PR Newswire | author=Aviation Partners, Inc. | date=January 15, 2013 | accessdate=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2015, United invested US$30 million in Fulcrum BioEnergy, an alternative fuel company. Fulcrum's alternative fuel is produced through a clean and efficient thermochemical process and reduces lifecycle carbon emissions by more than 80 percent. As part of its investment, United will work with Fulcrum to develop up to five alternative fuel refineries near its U.S. hubs. These refineries will produce up to 180 million gallons of sustainable aviation alternative fuel per year, and United will have the opportunity to purchase at least 90 million gallons per year for a minimum of 10 years, making it the largest aviation alternative fuel commitment to date.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://newsroom.united.com/2015-06-30-United-Airlines-Purchases-Stake-in-Fulcrum-BioEnergy-with-30-Million-Investment | title=United Airlines Purchases Stake in Fulcrum BioEnergy with $30 Million Investment | publisher=United Airlines | date=June 30, 2015 | accessdate=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2016, United became the first airline in the world to fly on commercial-scale quantities of such fuels on a continuous basis, which were procured from AltAir Fuels. This fuel was produced from sustainable feedstocks such as non-edible natural oils and agricultural wastes, and is expected to provide a greater than 60 percent reduction in carbon dioxide emissions on a lifecycle basis when compared to traditional jet fuel. United has agreed to purchase up to 15 million gallons of sustainable alternative fuel from AltAir Fuels for use in [[Los Angeles]] over a three-year period.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://newsroom.united.com/2016-03-11-United-Airlines-Makes-History-with-Launch-of-Regularly-Scheduled-Flights-Using-Sustainable-Biofuel|title=United Airlines Makes History with Launch of Regularly Scheduled Flights Using Sustainable Biofuel|publisher=United Airlines |date=March 11, 2016 |access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, United began partnering with [[Clean the World]] to repurpose items from the airline's international premium class amenity kits and donate the hygiene products to those in critical need. Clean the World provides hygiene education and soap to promote handwashing, which helps prevent hygiene-related deaths. During the first year of this partnership, United expected to divert {{convert|60000|lb|-2}} of material that otherwise would have gone to landfills.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://newsroom.united.com/2016-10-26-United-Airlines-and-Clean-the-World-Partner-to-Assemble-Hygiene-Kits-For-Hub-Based-Charities | title=United Airlines and Clean the World Partner to Assemble Hygiene Kits For Hub-Based Charities | publisher=United Airlines | date=October 26, 2016 | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 United started a partnership with [[Audubon International]] to protect raptors\u2014including hawks, ospreys and owls\u2014in and around New York-area airports and resettle the birds-of-prey at suitable golf course habitats where the species are more likely to thrive.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=http://newsroom.united.com/2017-07-24-United-Airlines-and-Audubon-International-Team-Up-to-Protect-Raptors-at-New-York-Area-Airports|title=United Airlines and Audubon International Team Up to Protect Raptors at New York-Area Airports|publisher=United Airlines |date=July 24, 2017 |access-date=2017-12-01}}</ref>\n\n===Worker relations===\nAll United Airlines pilots are represented by the [[Air Line Pilots Association]]. A new Joint Collective Bargaining Agreement was ratified by a majority of the United/Continental pilots on December 15, 2012,<ref name=\"pg13_10-K Form_Feb2012\">{{cite web|title=Form 10-K Filing|url=http://ir.unitedcontinentalholdings.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=83680&p=irol-SECText&TEXT=aHR0cDovL2FwaS50ZW5rd2l6YXJkLmNvbS9maWxpbmcueG1sP2lwYWdlPTgwODYzNjMmRFNFUT0xJlNFUT0xMyZTUURFU0M9U0VDVElPTl9QQUdFJmV4cD0%3d|work=United Airlines SEC filings|publisher=United Continental Holdings, Inc.|accessdate=6 January 2013|page=13}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Scope uncertainty pushes SkyWest to study large turboprops|first= Lori|last= Ranson|location= [[Washington, D.C.]]|publisher= [[Flightglobal.com]]|date= {{date|2011-9-2|mdy}}|url= http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/scope-uncertainty-pushes-skywest-to-study-large-turboprops-361562/|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190325055056/https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/scope-uncertainty-pushes-skywest-to-study-large-turboprops-361562/|archivedate= March 25, 2019|url-status= live|accessdate= {{date|2013-1-4|mdy}}}}</ref> which struck down a scope clause that disallowed Continental from outsourcing the flying of regional jets with 70 or more passenger seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887323297104578181302868464268.html |title=United Continental Pilots Approve Pact |author=Susan Carey |date=Dec 15, 2012 |work=The Wall Street Journal |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118004522/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887323297104578181302868464268.html |archive-date=January 18, 2013 |access-date=2013-08-16}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\n{{Main|List of United Airlines destinations|List of United Express destinations}}\nUnited operates to 238 domestic destinations and 118 international destinations in 48 countries or regions across five continents.<ref name=\"corporatefacts\">{{cite web |url=https://hub.united.com/corporate-fact-sheet/ |title=Corporate Fact Sheet |website=Hub |publisher=United Airlines |accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\n===Hubs===\nAs part of its [[Spoke\u2013hub distribution paradigm|hub-and-spoke]] business model, United currently operates eight [[Airline hub|hubs]] within the United States and its territories.<ref name=\"Airports and Terminal Maps\"/>\n*[[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]] \u2013 United's largest hub and its hub for the Midwest. United flies approximately 36 million passengers through O'Hare every year, which is about 99,000 people per day, making it also the busiest airline at the airport.<ref name=Chicago>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=29971 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Chicago O'Hare International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> United's corporate headquarters are also in Chicago.\n*[[Denver International Airport|Denver]] \u2013 United's fourth largest hub and its hub for the Rocky Mountain region of the United States.<ref name=Denver>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=29973 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Denver International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> In 2017, United flew approximately 25.9 million passengers through DIA or about 71,000 people per day.<ref name=Denver/> As of December 2017, United has about 42% of the market share at DIA making it the airport's largest airline.\n*[[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport|Guam]] - Inherited through the merger with Continental, Guam serves as United's hub for flight routes in the Pacific region.<ref name=\"Airports and Terminal Maps\"/> United has about 98.8% of the market share at Guam International, making it by far the largest airline at the airport. About 313,000 passengers flew through Guam between June 2018 and May 2019 on United, which is about 858 people per day.<ref name=\"BTS RITA Stats for GUM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transtats.bts.gov/airports.asp?pn=1&Airport=GUM&Airport_Name=Guam,%20TT:%20Guam%20International&carrier=FACTS |title=RITA &#124; BTS &#124; Transtats |publisher=Transtats.bts.gov |date=2016-02-24 |accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[George Bush Intercontinental Airport|Houston\u2013Intercontinental]] \u2013 Inherited through the merger with Continental, Houston-Intercontinental serves as United's second largest hub and its hub for the Southern United States. It is the primary gateway to Latin America.<ref name=Houston>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=29970 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Houston George Bush Intercontinental Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> About 33.5 million passengers fly through Houston on United every year, or about 91,000 people per day.<ref name=Houston/> United currently has about 78% of the seat share at Bush, making it the airport's largest tenant.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://centreforaviation.com/analysis/spirit-airlines-makes-a-new-push-from-houston-adding-some-new-competition-for-untied-and-southwest-200407 |title= Spirit Airlines makes a new push from Houston adding some new competition for United and Southwest |publisher= Centre for Aviation |accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref>\n*[[Los Angeles International Airport|Los Angeles]] \u2013 United's secondary hub for the West Coast and gateway to Asia and Australia.<ref name=LA>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/fact-sheet-lax | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Los Angeles International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> About 10 million passengers fly through LAX on United every year, or about 28,000 people per day.<ref name=LA/> United has 15% of the market share at LAX, making it the third-biggest carrier at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lawa.org/uploadedfiles/LAX/statistics/aircarrier-2015.pdf |title= Los Angeles International Airport Top 10 Carriers January 2015 through March 2015 |publisher= Los Angeles World Airports |accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref>\n*[[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark]] \u2013 Inherited through the merger with Continental, Newark is United's third largest hub and its primary hub for the New York City market and the Eastern Coast of the United States. It is United's primary gateway to Europe, while including other select flights to Latin America and Asia.<ref name=Newark>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=30000 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Liberty International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> About 28.5 million passengers fly on United through Newark every year, or about 78,000 people per day. United controls about 81% of the slots at Newark and carries about 68% of all passengers at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gao.gov/assets/660/655314.pdf|title= Issues Raised by the Proposed Merger of American Airlines and US Airways|publisher= GAO|accessdate= 2015-06-22|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150709130743/http://www.gao.gov/assets/660/655314.pdf|archive-date= July 9, 2015|url-status= dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.panynj.gov/airports/pdf-traffic/JUL2014_EWR.pdf |title= The Port Authority of NY & NJ July 2014 Traffic Report |publisher= The Port Authority of NY & NJ |accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> United controls all of Terminal C and also uses part of Terminal A for United Express.\n*[[San Francisco International Airport|San Francisco]] \u2013 United's fifth largest hub and its primary hub for the West Coast and gateway to Asia and Australia.<ref name=SanFran>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=29969 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, San Francisco International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> About 22 million passengers pass through SFO every year on United, which is about 60,000 people per day.<ref name=SanFran/> United has about 46% of the market share at San Francisco International, making it the biggest airline at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.flysfo.com/media/press-releases/sfo-announces-new-record-passenger-traffic-2013|title= SFO Announces New Record for Passenger Traffic in 2013 |publisher= San Francisco International Airport |accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> \n*[[Washington Dulles International Airport|Washington\u2013Dulles]] \u2013 United's secondary hub for the East Coast and gateway to Europe.<ref name=Washington>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/index.php?s=20306&item=29972 | title=Airport Fact Sheets, Washington Dulles International Airport | publisher=United Airlines | accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> United has about 65% of the market share at Washington Dulles, making it the largest airline at the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.metwashairports.com/file/ATS_Jan_2014.pdf |title= Air Traffic Statistics January 2014 |publisher= metwashairport.com |accessdate=2015-06-22}}</ref> About 14 million passengers fly through Dulles every year on United, which is about 38,465 people per day.<ref name=Washington/>\n\n===Alliance and codeshare agreements===\nUnited Airlines has been a member of the [[Star Alliance]] since the company was a co-founder in 1997.\n\nIt also has [[codeshare agreements]] with the following airlines:<ref name=\"CAPA United profile\">{{cite web | url=http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/united-airlines-ua | title=Profile on United Airlines | publisher=Centre for Aviation | accessdate=October 30, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030165942/http://centreforaviation.com/profiles/airlines/united-airlines-ua | archive-date=October 30, 2016 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Aer Lingus]]\n* [[Aeromar]]\n* [[Air Canada]]\n* [[Air China]]\n* [[Air India]]\n* [[Air Dolomiti]]\n* [[Air New Zealand]]\n* [[All Nippon Airways]]\n* [[Asiana Airlines]]\n* [[Austrian Airlines]]\n* [[Avianca]]\n* [[Azul Brazilian Airlines]]\n* [[Brussels Airlines]]\n* [[Cape Air]]\n* [[Copa Airlines]]\n* [[Croatia Airlines]]\n* [[EgyptAir]]\n* [[Ethiopian Airlines]]\n* [[Eurowings]]\n* [[EVA Air]]\n* [[Hawaiian Airlines]]\n* [[Island Air (Hawaii)|Island Air]]\n* [[LOT Polish Airlines]]\n* [[Lufthansa]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=United resumes Lufthansa codeshare to Russia from Feb 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288900/united-resumes-lufthansa-codeshare-to-russia-from-feb-2020/ |accessdate=20 January 2020 |work=Routesonline |date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Scandinavian Airlines]]\n* [[Silver Airways]]\n* [[Singapore Airlines]]\n* [[South African Airways]]\n* [[Swiss International Air Lines]]\n* [[TAP Air Portugal]]\n* [[Turkish Airlines]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Joint ventures===\nIn addition to the above codeshares, United has also entered into joint ventures with the following airlines:\n{{Div col|colwidth=17em}}\n*[[Air Canada]]<ref name=\"Joint Venture\">{{cite web | url=https://www.lufthansagroup.com/en/company/alliances/joint-ventures.html | title=Lufthansa Group: Joint Ventures | publisher=Lufthansa Group | accessdate=February 12, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212083513/https://www.lufthansagroup.com/en/company/alliances/joint-ventures.html | archive-date=February 12, 2019 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Air New Zealand]]\n*[[All Nippon Airways]]\n*[[Austrian Airlines]]<ref name=\"Joint Venture\" />\n*[[Brussels Airlines]]<ref name=\"Joint Venture\" />\n*[[Lufthansa]]<ref name=\"Joint Venture\" />\n*[[Swiss International Air Lines]]<ref name=\"Joint Venture\" />\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Fleet==\n[[File:N24976@PEK (20200421150836).jpg|thumb|A United Airlines Boeing 787-9 with new livery at [[Beijing Capital International Airport]].]]\n[[File:United Airlines a320 Friend Ship at SFO.jpg|alt=United Airlines Airbus A320 painted in the retro \"United Friend Ship\" livery at the gate at SFO Airport.|thumb|A United Airlines [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320]] painted in retro \"United Friend Ship\" livery sits at a gate at [[San Francisco International Airport]].]]<!--\nPlease do not add a fleet table to this section. Detailed fleet information is covered in the posted United Airlines fleet article.\n-->\n\n===Current fleet===\n{{Main|United Airlines fleet}}\n\nAs of October 2019, United Airlines operated a fleet of 790 aircraft; all [[Boeing]] and [[Airbus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.planespotters.net/airline/United-Airlines|title=United Airlines Fleet Details and History|last=|first=|date=|website=|accessdate=28 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Fleet strategy===\nOn July 20, 2011, [[American Airlines]] announced an order for 460 [[narrowbody]] jets, including 260 Airbus A320s.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://news.aa.com/press-releases/press-release-details/2011/AMR-Corporation-Announces-Largest-Aircraft-Order-in-History-With-Boeing-and-Airbus/default.aspx | title=AMR Corporation Announces Largest Aircraft Order in History With Boeing and Airbus | publisher=American Airlines | date=July 20, 2011}}</ref> The order broke Boeing's monopoly with the airline and forced Boeing to proceed with plans for the re-engined [[737 MAX]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/21/business/global/american-places-record-order-with-2-jet-makers.html | title=American Orders 460 Narrow Jets from Boeing and Airbus | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 20, 2011}}</ref> The contract with American included a [[Most-Favoured-Customer Clause]], which requires Airbus to refund to American any difference between the price paid by American and the price paid by United or another airline, if lower. The clause acts to perpetuate United having a Boeing-skewed fleet.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/united-goes-airframer-agnostic-on-future-orders-441837/ | title=United goes airframer 'agnostic' on future orders | date=October 4, 2017 | author=Edward Russell | work=Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\nOn September 22, 2012, United became the first American airline to take delivery of [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787]] aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing Delivers United Airlines' First 787 Dreamliner |url=https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2012-09-24-Boeing-Delivers-United-Airlines-First-787-Dreamliner |website=MediaRoom |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> United is also the North American launch customer for the Boeing 787-9<ref>{{cite news | url=http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2014-09-04-Boeing-Delivers-First-North-American-787-9-Dreamliner-to-United-Airlines | title=Boeing Delivers First North American 787-9 Dreamliner to United Airlines | work=Boeing | date=September 4, 2014}}</ref> and 787-10 aircraft,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://boeing.mediaroom.com/2013-06-18-Boeing-Launches-787-10-Dreamliner | title=Boeing Launches 787-10 Dreamliner | work=Boeing | date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> which are stretched versions of the base 787-8 model, delivered at launch.\n\nIn May 2018, United planned to replace its 51 Boeing 767s in a deal potentially worth $14 billion at list prices, and was in talks with both Airbus and Boeing, for their  [[A330neo]] and 787.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-united-aircraft-exclusive/united-airlines-in-talks-to-buy-wide-body-jets-sources-idUSKBN1I9361 |date= May 8, 2018 |title= Exclusive: United Airlines in talks to buy wide-body jets - sources |author= Tim Hepher, Alana Wise |agency= Reuters}}</ref>\nUnited operates 128 757s and 767s ({{#expr:56+21}} B757s and 51 B767s), the second-largest combined fleet after [[Delta Air Lines]] with 206 ({{#expr:111+16}} 757s and {{#expr:58+21}} 767s). Both have to replace them; they could be replaced by [[737 MAX|737 MAX 10]]s, [[A321neo]]s, [[Boeing New Midsize Airplane|Boeing NMA]]s, [[787-8]]s or [[Airbus A330neo|A330-800neo]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/analysis-united-weighs-timing-on-757-and-767-replac-449338/ |title= United weighs timing on 757 and 767 replacements |date= 11 June 2018 |author= Edward Russell |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n===Historical fleet===\n{{Main|History of United Airlines#Historical fleet}}\n\n==Cabin==\n[[File:United Polaris Seat.jpg|thumb|right|United Polaris business class seat on the Boeing 777-300ER]]\n\n===United Polaris Business===\n\nOn June 2, 2016, United introduced its new, redesigned international business class seat that will replace current business class seats. The Polaris seat converts into a 6' 6\" flat bed in a 1-2-1 configuration or a 1-1-1 configuration, providing all-aisle access for every seat. The seat boasts multiple storage areas, mood lighting, multiple charging ports, lumbar support, and improved dining and amenity services.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Airlines |first1=United |title=United Airlines Unveils Reimagined International Travel Experience - United Polaris Business Class |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/united-airlines-unveils-reimagined-international-travel-experience---united-polaris-business-class-300278706.html |website=www.prnewswire.com |accessdate=13 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThese seats can be found on select [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787]] aircraft, [[Boeing 767]] aircraft, and [[Boeing 777]] aircraft.\n \nUnited Polaris Business passengers check in at separate counters and can use priority security screening where available. On international flights, in-flight services include pre-departure beverages, table linens and multi course meals designed in partnership with [[Charlie Trotter]]-affiliated chefs via the airline's partnership with the Trotter Project.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Trotter Project: A culinary partnership takes flight|url=https://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/travel/inflight/dining/TheTrotterProject.aspx}}</ref> Passengers are also given priority with boarding and baggage handling and access to the United Polaris Lounge where available, as well as the [[United Club]] and partner airline lounges when traveling on international routes. All Polaris Business seats recline 180 degrees into a full, flat bed. On select Boeing 777-200ER and Boeing 767-300ER aircraft, the seats alternate facing forward and backwards. On the Boeing 787, Boeing 767-400, Boeing 757-200 and select Boeing 767-300ER and Boeing 777-200ER aircraft, all seats face forward.<ref>{{cite web |title=United Polaris FAQ |url=https://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/travel/inflight/united-polaris-FAQ.aspx |publisher=United Airlines |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=High-flying on United Airlines' Polaris business class |url=https://www.ttgmedia.com/news/features/high-flying-on-united-airlines-polaris-business-class-14635 |website=TTG |accessdate=13 March 2019 |language=En}}</ref>\n\nOther domestic routes, especially hub-to-hub service and certain non \"United p.s.\" transcontinental flights, regularly see internationally configured aircraft with United Polaris Business seating for operational reasons (such as transferring international aircraft from one hub to another). While the physical seats and entertainment are the same as on international flights, the service, catering and other amenities are the same as in domestic first class. Unlike routes marketed as United p.s., these flights are eligible for complimentary premier upgrades.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.united.com/ual/en/us/fly/mileageplus/premier/upgrades.html|title=United - Complimentary Premier Upgrades|website=United Airlines|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523062304/https://www.united.com/ual/en/us/fly/mileageplus/premier/upgrades.html|archive-date=23 May 2019|url-status=|access-date=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United Premium Plus===\n'''United Premium Plus''' will be United's premium economy product, to be installed through 2020 on wide-body international aircraft. United Premium Plus seating will offer more space, comfort and amenities compared to United Economy or Economy Plus, and will offer upgraded dining on china dinnerware, free alcoholic beverages, a Saks Fifth Avenue blanket and pillow, an amenity kit and more. United expects the first aircraft with these seats to be flying by mid-2018, with the full service launch in 2019. During the interim period, United will likely sell these seats as part of Economy Plus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/united-plans-premium-economy-launch-in-2019-447851/|title=United plans premium economy launch in 2019|date=2018-04-19|work=Flightglobal.com|access-date=2018-04-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===United premium transcontinental service===\n'''United premium transcontinental service''' is offered on transcontinental flights between Newark and Los Angeles or San Francisco and between Boston and San Francisco. Previously branded as '''p.s.''' (short for \"Premium Service\") when initially launched in 2004, through 2017, these flights utilize primarily Boeing 757-200s, with 180-degrees-flat Polaris Business seats. The premium cabin also features international style catering, while all seats have access to inflight wi-fi, on demand entertainment, and power outlets. Business class passengers also have access to the United Club at Newark, Boston, Los Angeles, and San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ir.united.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=83680&p=RssLanding&cat=news&id=1797405 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904030716/http://ir.united.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=83680&p=RssLanding&cat=news&id=1797405 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2015-09-04 |title=United Airlines Revamps Cabins, Adds Flat-Bed Seating on \"p.s.\" Flights |publisher=united.com |date=2013-03-18 |accessdate=2014-01-30 }}</ref>\n\nAll premium transcontinental flights were moved from New York JFK to Newark Liberty Airport on October 25, 2015.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://hub.united.com/en-us/news/products-services/pages/united-strengthens-new-york-new-jersey-hub-with-ps-premium-service.aspx |title=We're Bringing Premium Transcontinental Service to our New York/Newark Hub |publisher=United Airlines |date=2015-06-16 |accessdate=2015-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905100109/https://hub.united.com/en-us/news/products-services/pages/united-strengthens-new-york-new-jersey-hub-with-ps-premium-service.aspx |archive-date=September 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThese routes are not eligible for Complimentary Premier upgrades, although MileagePlus members can upgrade using Regional Premier Upgrades, Global Premier Upgrades, or MileagePlus award miles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/mileageplus/awards/upgrade/default.aspx |title=Upgrades Overview |publisher=united.com |accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n\nSince July 2017, passengers in this class get a complimentary hot entree, dessert, fruit, pre-arrival snack, and alcoholic beverages.<ref name=\"united.com1\">{{cite press release|title=Cross Country Comfort: Introducing United Airlines' New Transcontinental Service|date=May 31, 2017|publisher=United Airlines|url=http://newsroom.united.com/2017-05-31-Cross-Country-Comfort-Introducing-United-Airlines-New-Transcontinental-Service|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref>\n\n===United First and United Business===\n'''United First''' is offered on all domestically configured aircraft. When such aircraft are used on international services such as services to Canada, Central America and the Caribbean destinations, this cabin is branded as '''United Business'''. United First seats on narrowbody aircraft have a {{convert|38|in|cm|adj=mid}} [[seat pitch]], while United First seats on re-configured domestic Boeing 777-200 aircraft feature fully flat bed seats. Passengers receive priority boarding and baggage handling, pre-departure beverages, complimentary meals and separate check-in desks.<ref>{{cite web|last=TripAdvisor|title=United Airlines Information|url=http://www.seatguru.com/airlines/United_Airlines/information.php|publisher=seatguru.com|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, United released its new domestic first class seat design. The new leather seats feature cradling headrests, granite cocktail tables, and a tablet stand. These seats will debut on [[Airbus A319]] and [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320]] aircraft, and will eventually be installed on all domestic aircraft.<ref>{{cite AV media|publisher=YouTube|title=Introducing the new United aircraft cabin design|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m0fcpclVjSE|accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, It was announced that United is increasing first and business class seats \"by 1,600\" across all their aircraft in their fleet, to include the [[Bombardier CRJ700 series#CRJ550|Bombardier CRJ550]] for which United is the \"launch customer\" of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airwaysmag.com/airlines/first-united-crj550-spotted-in-chicago/ |date=August 8, 2019 |title=Photos: First United Airlines CRJ-550 Spotted in Chicago |work=[[Airways (magazine)|Airways]] |accessdate=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Economy Plus===\n[[File:United Airlines Boeing 767-300ER Economy Seats.JPG|thumb|Economy plus seats on a [[Boeing 767]]]]\n'''United Economy Plus''' is available on all aircraft. Economy Plus seats are located in the front few rows and exit rows of the economy cabin and have {{convert|2|in|cm}} more recline and at least {{convert|5|to|6|in|cm}} of additional seat pitch totaling {{convert|4|to|7|in|cm}} of recline (aircraft dependent) and {{convert|35|to|37|in|cm}} of pitch. Economy Plus is complimentary for all [[MileagePlus]] Premier members. Premier 1K, Platinum and Gold members may select an Economy Plus seat when booking, while silver members can select an Economy Plus seat at check-in.<ref>{{cite web |title=Economy Plus |url=https://www.united.com/CMS/en-US/products/travelproducts/Pages/EconomyPlus.aspx |publisher=United Airlines}}</ref> It can also be purchased depending upon availability by other passengers.\n[[File:United_Airlines_Wing_and_Economy_Plus_Seat.jpg|thumb|Economy plus seating with view of wing]]\nPrior to the merger between United and Continental, United Airlines aircraft offered Economy Plus, while Continental did not. Following the merger, Economy Plus was rolled out across the combined fleet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/United-Airlines-to-Retain-prnews-2471080087.html?x=0&.v=1 |title=United Airlines to Retain Economy Plus, Expand to Continental Aircraft Beginning in 2012 |website=Yahoo! Finance |date=March 6, 2011 |accessdate=April 10, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306114029/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/United-Airlines-to-Retain-prnews-2471080087.html?x=0&.v=1 |archivedate=March 6, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Economy===\n[[File:Uniteds new Recaro seats (10360311066).jpg|thumb|right|New slimline economy seats on an [[Airbus A320 family|Airbus A320-200]]]]\n'''United Economy''' is available on all aircraft, and usually have a pitch of 31 inches (30 inches on aircraft refurbished with Slimline seats, and 32 inches on Boeing 787s) and a recline of 2\u20135 inches. All economy seats feature an adjustable headrest and some form of entertainment, ranging from [[AVOD]], inflight wi-fi, personal device entertainment, or [[DirecTV]]. Economy seats on Boeing 767, Boeing 777 (except domestic 777-200s), Boeing 787, and 757-200 aircraft feature a personal {{convert|7|in|cm|adj=mid}} touchscreen television at the back of each seat with United Private Screening. On Airbus A319, A320, Boeing 737, Boeing 757-300, and domestically configured Boeing 777 aircraft feature personal device entertainment and WiFi. Some Boeing 737 aircraft feature DirecTV.<ref>{{cite web|title=DirectTV - United Airlines|url=https://www.united.com/CMS/en-US/travel/Pages/DIRECTV.aspx}}</ref> In April 2018, United upgraded all aircraft with over 70 seats to include Wi-Fi and personal device entertainment even with DirecTV equipped.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thepointsguy.com/news/united-updates-its-fleet-to-add-free-entertainment-options/|title=United Updates Its Fleet to Add Free Entertainment Options|work=The Points Guy|access-date=2018-06-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nFood and snacks are available for purchase on domestic, Caribbean, and some Latin America flights. These include snacks, fresh meals, and snack boxes, depending on flight time and distance. Meals are complimentary on all other international flights. Only beverages are complimentary in economy on North America flights. Alcoholic beverages are available for purchase on North America flights, but are complimentary on long-haul international flights.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Beverage Service|url=https://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/travel/inflight/dining/beverages/default.aspx|website=United.com}}</ref> On flights where meals are served, a cocktail snack with a beverage is served shortly after takeoff, followed by a main course, then dessert. Longer international flights feature a pre-arrival meal, which usually consists of a light breakfast or snack. United announced that it would offer free snacks on domestic, Caribbean, and Latin America flights, which began in February 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fottrell |first=Quentin |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/united-airlines-brings-back-free-snacks-2015-12-09?siteid=rss&rss=1 |title=United joins this very short list of airlines that still give you 'free' snacks |website=MarketWatch |date=2015-12-11 |accessdate=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n===Basic Economy===\n'''[[Basic Economy]]''' is available on select routes and in addition to standard fares. Intended to be United's lowest fare, Basic Economy fares provide most of the same inflight services and amenities with standard United Economy Class.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/united-airlines-launches-basic-economy-184000342.html|title=United Airlines Launches New Basic Economy Fare for Twin Cities Travel|work=Yahoo! Finance|via=PR Newswire|date=22 February 2017|access-date=22 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170223052145/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/united-airlines-launches-basic-economy-184000342.html|archive-date=February 23, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> With Basic Economy, group/family seating, seat selection/upgrades and bringing full-sized carry-on bags are not allowed. When booking online, it is clearly marked - with a user prompt to confirm the user is booking a Basic Economy fare. Users also have the option to pay a small fee to upgrade their booking to regular Economy. Also, certain MileagePlus and Premier member benefits are not available.<ref>{{cite web|title=Basic Economy|url=https://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/travel/inflight/basic-economy.aspx|website=United|access-date=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reward services==\n[[MileagePlus]] is the frequent flyer program for United Airlines.<ref name=\"mileage plus\">{{cite web |title=Mileage Plus |url=https://www.united.com/web/en-US/content/mileageplus/default.aspx |website=United.com |publisher=United Airlines |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[United Club]] is the airline lounge associated with United Airlines and United Express carriers. The United Club replaced the former United Red Carpet Club and Continental Airlines Presidents Club prior to United Airlines' merger with [[Continental Airlines|Continental]].<ref name=\"United Club\">{{cite web|title=United Club Changes|url=https://hub.united.com/en-us/news/company-operations/pages/united-club-is-the-new-name.aspx|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121217204009/https://hub.united.com/en-us/news/company-operations/pages/united-club-is-the-new-name.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 December 2012|work=United Airlines web site|publisher=United Airlines|accessdate=5 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Concerns and conflicts==\n===Animal transport===\nIn 2013, after pressure from [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]], United announced that it would no longer transport monkeys to laboratories. United was the last North American passenger airline to transport these animals to laboratories.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wadman|first1=Meredith|title=United Airlines ends transport of research primates|url=http://blogs.nature.com/news/2013/01/united-airlines-ends-transport-of-research-primates.html|accessdate=28 January 2015|journal=Nature|date=8 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Stuart|first1=Hunter|title=PETA: United Airlines Will No Longer Fly Monkeys For Use In Lab Experiments|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/09/peta-united-airlines-lab-monkeys-lab-experiments_n_2439499.html|accessdate=28 January 2015|work=Huffington Post|date=9 January 2013}}</ref> United flies more animals and has longer flight stage length than any other US airline, and accounted for one third of animal deaths of US airlines between 2012 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2017/04/26/united-airlines-animal-deaths-flights/100925100/ | title = United Airlines accounted for a third of animal deaths on U.S. flights in last 5 years | work = [[USA Today]] | last = Jansen | first = Bart | date = April 26, 2017 | accessdate = July 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nEffective March 20, 2018, the PetSafe program was suspended with no new reservations for cargo transport of pets accepted.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Aaron |url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/03/20/news/companies/united-airlines-pets/index.html |title=United suspends pet cargo flights |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2018-03-20 |accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref> This came after United announced plans to mark pet carriers in the passenger cabin with bright tags<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=http://wgntv.com/2018/03/15/united-airlines-to-use-special-tags-for-pet-carriers-after-dog-death/ |title=United Airlines to use special tags for pet carriers after dog death |publisher=WGN-TV |date=2018-03-15 |accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref> and legislation was introduced in the United States House of Representatives<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cohen.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/donovan-cohen-introduce-bipartisan-bill-banning-pets-overhead |title=Donovan, Cohen Introduce Bipartisan Bill Banning Pets from Overhead Compartments &#124; Congressman Steve Cohen |publisher=Cohen.house.gov |date=2018-03-15 |accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref> and United States Senate banning the placement of pets in overhead compartments.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2018/03/15/senator-plans-file-bill-prohibiting-airlines-from-putting-pets-overhead-bins/z0hwvXyN8c78vlWEJBAPkJ/story.html |title=Senator plans to file bill prohibiting airlines from putting pets in overhead bins |newspaper=The Boston Globe |accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref> This was in response to a  dog death after a passenger placed it in the overhead compartment following flight attendant instructions, but the flight attendant denied knowing that the luggage contained a dog.<ref>{{cite web |author=Liam Stack |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/13/business/united-dead-dog.html |title=United Airlines Apologizes After Dog Dies in Overhead Compartment |work=The New York Times |date=2018-03-13 |accessdate=2018-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Cyber security issues===\nUnited awarded airline miles as \"bug bounties\" to hackers who could identify gaps in the carrier's web security. Two hackers have each been rewarded with 1 million miles of air travel as of July 15, 2015. This cyber security program was announced a few weeks before the company experienced two software glitches. The first incident delayed 150 United flights on June 2 due to a problem with its flight dispatching system. Six days later, United's reservation system delayed flights by not allowing passengers to check in. In addition to the \"bug bounty\" program, United said it tests systems internally and engages cybersecurity firms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dastin|first1=Jeffrey|title=United Airlines awards hackers millions of miles for revealing risks|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/16/us-cybersecurity-airmiles-idUSKCN0PQ0A320150716|accessdate=16 July 2015|work=Reuters|date=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bogage|first1=Jacob|title=Why United Airlines is rewarding hackers with millions of free miles|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2015/07/16/why-united-airlines-is-rewarding-hackers-with-millions-of-free-miles/|accessdate=16 July 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=16 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Privacy concerns===\nIn February 2019, privacy concerns arose after it emerged that United had installed cameras in some seat backs. United said that the cameras were \"not activated\", but journalists reported that malicious hackers could still potentially enable the cameras to spy on passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/2/22/18235979/camera-airplane-inflight-entertainment-american-singapore-airlines-privacy|title=Discovery of cameras built into airlines' seats sparks privacy concerns|first=Jon|last=Porter|date=February 22, 2019|website=The Verge|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nicolenguyen/american-airlines-planes-entertainment-system-cameras|title=People Are Worried About Singapore Airlines' Entertainment System Cameras. Turns Out, American Airlines Has Cameras, Too.|website=BuzzFeed News|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/world/three-airlines-confirm-some-of-their-aircraft-have-cameras-in-their-seatback-entertainment-screens-a4074741.html|title=Airlines admit to having cameras in their seat entertainment screens|date=February 23, 2019|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://boingboing.net/2019/02/20/singapore-airlines-says-seatba.html|title=Singapore Airlines says seatback cameras are \"disabled\"|website=Boing Boing|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/airplane-seat-cameras-could-be-your-new-spy-in-the-sky/|title=Airplane seat cameras could be your new spy in the sky|first=Claire|last=Reilly|website=CNET|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|1930s\n|[[United Airlines Chesterton Crash|NC13304]]\n|[[1934 United Airlines Utah crash|NC13357]]\n|[[Boeing 247#Accidents and incidents|Flight 6]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 4|Flight 4]]<ref>{{cite book|author=F. Robert Van der Linden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zTueJhXW0QC&lpg=PP19&pg=PA174#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=The Boeing 247: The First Modern Airliner|publisher=University of Washington Press |accessdate=May 3, 2010|isbn=9780295970943|date=1991-12-01|page=174}}</ref>\n|United Airlines Cheynne Test Crash|NC13323<ref>{{cite book|author=F. Robert Van der Linden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zTueJhXW0QC&lpg=PP19&pg=PA175#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=The Boeing 247: The First Modern Airliner|publisher=University of Washington Press|accessdate=May 3, 2010|isbn=9780295970943|date=1991-12-01|page=175}}</ref>\n|[[United Airlines Trip 34|NC13355]]<ref>{{cite book|author=F. Robert Van der Linden|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zTueJhXW0QC&lpg=PP19&pg=PA186#v=onepage&q=&f=false |title=The Boeing 247: The First Modern Airliner|publisher=University of Washington Press|accessdate=May 3, 2010|isbn=9780295970943|date=1991-12-01|page=186}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|1940s\n|[[1943 Liberator crash at Whenuapai|41-24027]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 521|Flight 521]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 608|Flight 608]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 624|Flight 624]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1950s\n|United Airlines Flight 129|Flight 129<ref>{{ASN accident|title=N16088|id=19510428-1|accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>\n|[[United Airlines Flight 610|Flight 610]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 615|Flight 615]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 409|Flight 409]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 629|Flight 629]]\n|[[1956 Grand Canyon mid-air collision|Flight 718]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 736|Flight 736]]\n|-\n|1960s\n|[[1960 New York mid-air collision|Flight 826]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 859|Flight 859]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 297|Flight 297]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 823|Flight 823]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 389|Flight 389]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 227|Flight 227]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 266|Flight 266]]\n|-\n|1970s\n|[[United Airlines Flight 553|Flight 553]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 2860|Flight 2860]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 696|Flight 696]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 173|Flight 173]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1980s\n|[[United Airlines Flight 811|Flight 811]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 232|Flight 232]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 2885|Flight 2885]]\n|[[United Express Flight 2415|Flight 2415]]\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|1990s\n|[[United Airlines Flight 585|Flight 585]]\n|[[United Express Flight 6291|Flight 6291]]\n|[[United Express Flight 5925|Flight 5925]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 826 (1997)|Flight 826]] \n|[[United Airlines Flight 863|Flight 863]] \n|\n|\n|-\n|2000s\n|[[United Airlines Flight 175|Flight 175]]\n|[[United Airlines Flight 93|Flight 93]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|2010s\n|[[United Airlines Flight 3411|Flight 3411]]\n|Flight 627\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n<!--Commenting out this section for now since it is really trivia, see talk section. \n===Dave Carroll Guitar===\nIn 2008, United baggage handlers broke Canadian musician [[Dave Carroll (musician)|Dave Carroll]]'s guitar. After nine months fruitlessly trying to resolve the situation, Carroll released three songs about the incident. The first, ''[[United Breaks Guitars]]'', has over 17 million views as of 2017, and caused a significant public relations embarrassment for the airline.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sentium.com/a-public-relations-disaster-how-saving-1200-cost-united-airlines-10772839-negative-views-on-youtube/ | title=How saving $1,200 cost United Airlines 10,772,839 negative views on YouTube | work=Sentium Strategic Communications | author=Richard Wilson | accessdate=July 23, 2017}}</ref>\n-->\n\n===United 3411===\n{{main|United Express Flight 3411 incident}}\n\nOn the evening of April 9, 2017, a revenue passenger was forcibly removed by law enforcement from United Airlines flight 3411 at [[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago-O'Hare]], bound for [[Louisville International Airport|Louisville]].<ref name=\"bbc17\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39554421 | title=United Airlines: Passenger forcibly removed from flight | date=April 10, 2017 | website=BBC.com}}</ref> United announced that it needed four seats for airline staff on the sold-out flight.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2017/04/11/united-ceo-employees-followed-procedures-flier-belligerent/100317166/ | title=United Airlines now says flight that sparked uproar was not overbooked | author=John Bacon | date=April 11, 2017 | work=USA TODAY | accessdate=April 11, 2017 | language=en}}</ref> When no passengers volunteered after being offered vouchers worth $800, United staff selected four passengers to leave. Three of them did so, but the fourth, a doctor named David Dao, declined as he said that he had patients to treat the following morning. He was pulled from his seat by [[Chicago Department of Aviation]] security officers and dragged by his arms down the aisle. Dao sustained a concussion, broken teeth, a broken nose, and other injuries.<ref>{{cite news | author=Mitch Smith | title=United Airlines Passenger May Need Surgery, Lawyer Says | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/13/us/united-passenger-david-dao-chicago.html?_r=0 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> The incident was captured on smartphone cameras and posted on social media, triggering an angry public backlash. Afterwards, United's chief executive officer, [[Oscar Munoz (executive)|Oscar Munoz]], described Dao as \"disruptive and belligerent\", apologized for \"re-accommodating\" the paying customers, and defended and praised staff for \"following established procedures\". He was widely criticized as \"tone-deaf\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2017/04/11/tone-deaf-united-ceo-thinks-things-are-going-just-fine/|title=Tone-deaf United CEO thinks things are going just fine | author=Todd Venezla | date=April 11, 2017 | newspaper=[[New York Post]] | accessdate=April 17, 2017 | language=en}}</ref> Munoz later issued a second statement calling what happened a \"truly horrific event\" and accepting \"full responsibility\" for it.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/04/11/news/companies/united-munoz-apology/ | title=United CEO apologizes for 'truly horrific' passenger incident | author=John Ostrower | date=April 12, 2017 | work=CNN Money | accessdate=April 17, 2017 | language=en}}</ref> After a lawsuit, Dao reached an undisclosed settlement with United and airport police. In the aftermath, United's board of directors decided that Munoz would not become its chairman and that executive compensation would be tied to customer satisfaction.<ref>{{cite news | title=United Airlines to tie executive pay to customer satisfaction | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39675265 | accessdate=April 23, 2017 | work=BBC News | date=April 22, 2017}}</ref> Following this incident, passenger complaints increased by 70 percent.<ref>{{cite news | title=Airline customer complaints soar following terrible April | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/14/airline-customer-complaints-soar-following-terrible-april.html | author=Phil LeBeau | publisher=CNBC | date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Air transport in the United States]]\n* [[Transportation in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Mouawad2\">\n{{cite news|title=On Jet Exteriors, a Parade of Vanilla |page=1 |first=Jad |last=Mouawad |work=New York Times |date=2011-12-2