ited-airlines-jane-garvey-board-chairman-0525-story.html|title=United taps FAA trailblazer as airline's first female board chairman|first=Lauren|last=Zumbach|website=chicagotribune.com}}</ref>\n* Gerry Laderman<br />{{small|([[Chief Financial Officer]])}}<ref name=\"united.com\">{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/2016-08-18-United-Appoints-New-Senior-Leaders | title=News Releases|website=Newsroom.united.com}}</ref>\n* [[Walter Varney]]<br />{{small|([[Organizational founder|Founder]])}}\n| revenue = {{Increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]43.259 billion {{small|(2019)}}<ref name=\"10-K\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/319687/000010051720000010/ual201910k.htm |title=United Airliens, Inc. 2019 Annual Report (Form 10-K) |date=February 2020 |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |access-date=17 March 2020 |website=sec.gov}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{Increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]4.301 billion {{small|(2019)}}<ref name=\"10-K\"/>\n| net_income = {{Increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]3.009 billion {{small|(2019)}}<ref name=\"10-K\"/>\n| assets = {{Increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]52.611 billion {{small|(2019)}}<ref name=\"10-K\"/>\n| equity = {{Increase}} [[United States dollar|$]]11.531 billion {{small|(2019)}}<ref name=\"10-K\"/>\n| website = [https://www.united.com united.com]\n}}\n\n'''United Airlines, Inc.''' (commonly referred to as '''United''') is a [[Major airlines of the United States|major American]] airline headquartered at [[Willis Tower]] in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web | title=United Technical Operations | url=http://www.unitedtechops.com/ | website=www.unitedtechops.com | accessdate=January 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web | url=https://sites.google.com/site/unitedfleetsite/mainline-fleet-tracking | title=United Mainline Fleet - The United Airlines Fleet Website | website=google.com | accessdate=April 3, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">[http://www.united.com/web/en-us/content/travel/destination/routes/served.aspx Destinations Served]. United Airlines Official Statistics.</ref> United operates a large domestic and international route network spanning cities large and small across the [[United States]] and all six continents.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.staralliance.com/assets/doc/en/about/member-airlines/pdf/Facts_and_Figures_as_of_31MAR2014_Final.pdf | title=Star Alliance Facts and Figures | publisher=Star Alliance | date=March 31, 2014 | accessdate=April 4, 2014 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016050926/http://www.staralliance.com/assets/doc/en/about/member-airlines/pdf/Facts_and_Figures_as_of_31MAR2014_Final.pdf | archivedate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\nMeasured by fleet size and number of routes, it is the [[Largest airlines in the world|third largest airline]] in the world. It is a founding member of the [[Star Alliance]], the world's largest airline alliance with a total of 28 member airlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/larryolmsted/2017/12/21/best-worst-of-aviation-2017-airlines-and-alliances/#667099d82556|title=Best & Worst Of Aviation 2017: Airlines And Alliances|last=Olmsted|first=Larry|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-03-12|language=en}}</ref> Regional service is operated by independent carriers under the brand name [[United Express]]. United was established by the amalgamation of several airlines in the late 1920s, the oldest of these being Varney Air Lines, which was founded in 1926.<ref name=\"varney\"/>\n\nUnited has eight hubs, with [[O'Hare International Airport|Chicago\u2013O'Hare]] being its largest in terms of passengers carried and the number of departures.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/flights/todayinthesky/2017/01/26/fleet-and-hubs-united-airlines-numbers/96983530/ | title=The Fleet and Hubs of United Airlines, by the Numbers | newspaper=USA Today | date=January 26, 2017 | accessdate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of United Airlines}}\nUnited traces its roots to [[Varney Air Lines]] (VAL), which [[Walter Varney]] founded in 1926 in [[Boise, Idaho]]. [[Continental Airlines]] is the successor to Speed Lanes, which Varney had founded by 1932 and whose name changed to Varney Speed Lines in 1934. VAL flew the first privately contracted [[air mail]] flight in the U.S. on April 6, 1926.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nvahof.org/hof/hof-2011/walter-t-varney/ | title=Walter T. Varney | publisher=[[Nevada Aerospace Hall of Fame]] | year=2011 | accessdate=February 19, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033206/http://www.nvahof.org/hof/hof-2011/walter-t-varney/ | archive-date=February 20, 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.smdailyjournal.com/article_preview.php?type=lnews&title=Walter%20Varney%20Airfield%20and%20United%20Airlines&id=147055 | title=Walter Varney Airfield and United Airlines | author=Darold Fredericks | date=November 29, 2010 | newspaper=[[San Mateo Daily Journal]] | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220201830/http://smdailyjournal.com/article_preview.php?type=lnews&title=Walter%20Varney%20Airfield%20and%20United%20Airlines&id=147055 | archivedate=December 20, 2010 | accessdate=February 19, 2018 | url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=History of Flight in the US \u2013 Seventy-Five Years United | author1=David Fuscher | author2=Bill Garvey | url=http://www.flatrock.org.nz/topics/flying/seventy_five_years.htm | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116104852/http://flatrock.org.nz/topics/flying/seventy_five_years.htm | archivedate=January 16, 2013 | url-status=live | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1927, [[William Boeing]] founded Boeing Air Transport to operate air mail routes under contract with the [[United States Post Office Department]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boeing.com/history/chronology/chron03.html | title=The Boeing Logbook: 1927\u20131932 | publisher=Boeing | accessdate=February 19, 2018 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804001157/http://www.boeing.com/history/chronology/chron03.html | archivedate=August 4, 2012}}</ref> In 1929, Boeing merged his company with [[Pratt & Whitney]] to form the [[United Aircraft and Transport Corporation]] (UATC) which then set about buying, in the space of just 28 months, [[Pacific Air Transport]], [[Stout Air Services]], VAL, and [[National Air Transport]], as well as numerous equipment manufacturers at the same time.<ref name=\"history_FundingUniverse\">{{cite web |title=History of UAL Corporation |url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/ual-corporation-history/ |publisher=FundingUniverse |accessdate= December 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>Davies ''Air Enthusiast'' January/February 2007, page 74</ref> On March 28, 1931, UATC formed United Air Lines, Inc. as a holding company for its airline subsidiaries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.united.com/page/article/0,6722,2296,00.html |publisher=United Airlines |title=Timeline (entry for March 28, 1931) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040315102458/http://www.united.com/page/article/0,6722,2296,00.html |archive-date=March 15, 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2006, Continental Airlines and United had preliminary merger discussions.<ref name=\"wsj_20061213_co_ua_fl_yx\">{{cite news | url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB116597376254248407.html | title=UAL, Continental Discuss Merger As AirTran Presses Bid for Midwest | author1=S. Carey | author2=M. Trottman | author3=D. K. Berman | newspaper=The Wall Street Journal | date=December 13, 2006}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt_20061212\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/12/business/12cnd-air.html?hp&ex=1165986000&en=ac06dd7e47ab6102&ei=5094&partner=homepage | title=United and Continental Discussing Possible Merger | author1=Andrew Ross Sorkin | author2=Jeff Bailey | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 12, 2006 | accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref> On April 16, 2010, those discussions resumed.<ref name=\"UA-CO merger talks resumed\">{{cite news | author1=Jad Mouawad | title=Continental and United Are in Merger Talks Again | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/16/business/16air.html?_r=0 | accessdate=December 20, 2012 | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 15, 2010 | author2=Andrew Ross Sorkin}}</ref> The board of directors of Continental and UAL Corporation agreed on May 2, 2010, to combine operations, contingent upon shareholder and regulatory approval. On October 1, 2010, the UAL Corporation changed its name to United Continental Holdings, Inc.<ref>{{cite web | author=Thomas J. Sabatino, Jr. | title=Form 8-K Continental Airlines Inc. | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/319687/000119312510222187/d8k.htm | website=sec.org | publisher=United States Securities and Exchange Commission | accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref> The carriers planned to begin merging their operations in 2011.<ref name=\"sfgate.com\">{{cite news | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/09/19/BU7H1FGCIJ.DTL | newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]] | title=United, Continental to merge operations in 2011 | date=September 20, 2010}}</ref> The merged airline began operating under a single [[air operator's certificate]] from the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] on November 30, 2011.<ref>{{cite news | title=FAA approves single operating certificate for United, Continental merger | author=Linda Blachly | publisher=[[Air Transport World]] | date=December 1, 2011 | url=http://atwonline.com/international-aviation-regulation/news/faa-approves-single-operating-certificate-united-continental- | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205170514/http://atwonline.com/international-aviation-regulation/news/faa-approves-single-operating-certificate-united-continental- | archivedate=February 5, 2012 | url-status=dead | accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> On March 3, 2012, United and Continental merged their passenger service systems, frequent-flier programs, and websites, which virtually eliminated the Continental brand with the exception of its logo.<ref name=\"Riegler\">{{cite news | author=Paul Riegler | title=United and Continental Complete Computer System and Web Site Merger | url=http://www.frequentbusinesstraveler.com/2012/03/united-and-continental-complete-computer-system-and-web-site-merger/ | agency=Frequent Business Traveler}}</ref> On June 27, 2019, the parent company's name changed from United Continental Holdings to [[United Airlines Holdings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-06-27/united-airlines-strips-continental-from-parent-company-s-name|title=United Airlines Strips 'Continental' from parent company's name|accessdate=June 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n===Ownership and structure===\nUnited Airlines, Inc. is publicly traded through its parent company, [[United Airlines Holdings]]. Inc, which is a [[Delaware General Corporation Law|Delaware corporation]],<ref name=\"2018 Report\"/> on the New York Stock Exchange {{NYSE|UAL}}, with a [[market capitalization]] of over US$21 billion as of January 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsroom.united.com/2018-01-23-United-Airlines-Reports-Fourth-Quarter-and-Full-Year-2017-Performance | title=United Airlines Reports Fourth-Quarter and Full-Year 2017 Performance | date=January 23, 2018 | website=newsroom.united.com | accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref> United's operating revenues and operating expenses comprise nearly 100% of the holding company's revenues and operating expenses.<ref name=\"2018 Report\"/>\n\n===Business trends===\nThe key trends for the United Airlines Holdings, Inc. group (formerly the United Continental Holdings, Inc. group), including its consolidated subsidiaries, are (years ending December&nbsp;31):\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | \n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2012</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2013</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2014</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2015</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2016</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2017</span>\n! style=\"background: #005DAA;\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">2018</span>\n|-\n| Turnover ([[United States dollar|$]]m)\n| align=center|37,152\n| align=center|38,279\n| align=center|38,901\n| align=center|37,864\n| align=center|36,558\n| align=center|37,784\n! align=center|41,303\n|-\n| Net profit after tax ($m)\n| align=center|{{color|red|&minus;723}}\n| align=center|571\n| align=center|1,132\n| align=center|7,340\n| align=center|2,234\n| align=center|2,144\n! align=center|2,129\n|-\n| Number of employees (average [[Full time equivalent|FTE]])(000s)\n| align=center|84.6\n| align=center|84.2\n| align=center|82.0\n| align=center|82.1\n| align=center|83.9\n| align=center|86.0\n! align=center|86.6\n|-\n| Number of passengers (m)\n| align=center|140.4\n| align=center|139.2\n| align=center|138.0\n| align=center|140.4\n| align=center|143.2\n| align=center|148.1\n! align=center|158.3\n|-\n| Passenger load factor (%)\n| align=center|82.6\n| align=center|83.6\n| align=center|83.6\n| align=center|83.4\n| align=center|82.9\n| align=center|82.4\n! align=center|83.6\n|-\n| Number of aircraft (at year end)\n| align=center|1,253\n| align=center|1,265\n| align=center|1,257\n| align=center|1,239\n| align=center|1,231\n| align=center|1,263\n! align=center|1,329\n|-\n| <small>''Notes/sources''</small>\n| align=center|<ref name=\"2013 Report\"/>\n| align=center|<ref name=\"2013 Report\">{{cite web |title=United Airlines Reports Fourth-Quarter and Full-Year 2013 Performance |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/united-announces-